<subSubSection id="48D355CA8EEFFF6148F757B4FDD0FECF" pageId="161" pageNumber="162" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="007606418EEFFF6148F757B4FDD0FECF" blockId="161.[151,1439,151,2010]" pageId="161" pageNumber="162">Remarks. The enlarged claw of A. raptor is extraordinary among dryinids, because usually, when the chela is closed, the distal apex of the enlarged claw is inserted in the group of lamellae situated at distal apex of segment 5 of protarsus; for this reason, usually the enlarged claw is about as long as segment 5 of protarsus; however, in A. raptor, when the chela is closed, the enlarged claw is so long, that its distal apex reaches segment 2 of protarsus; no dryinids in the world show a similar chela.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
